# =============================================================================
# .clinerules — Medical WebApp (Hospital ERP)
# FastAPI + React 19 + TypeScript 6 + PostgreSQL | Windows 11 / PowerShell
# =============================================================================
# This file governs AI-assisted development behaviour for this monorepo.
# It is NOT a style guide — it is an execution contract.
# =============================================================================

# =============================================================================
# 1. GENERAL CODING RULES
# =============================================================================
# - Use Python 3.11+ type hints everywhere (from __future__ import annotations).
# - Prefer explicit imports over wildcard imports (no `from x import *`).
# - Use `| None` over `Optional[]` for nullable types.
# - Use `Self` return type for class methods returning `self`.
# - Use `Session` from SQLAlchemy, never raw connections in service/crud layers.
# - Use `UUID` for all primary/foreign keys (not int).
# - Use `text()` from SQLAlchemy for raw SQL, never string interpolation.
# - Use `contextlib.contextmanager` or `@asynccontextmanager` for resource lifecycle.
# - Use `logging` over `print()` for all diagnostic output.
# - Use `from __future__ import annotations` at top of every Python file.
# - Prefer `pydantic` BaseSettings / BaseModel for configuration and schemas.
# - Use `@property` for computed fields, never bare methods named `get_*` for simple accessors.
# - Use `enum.StrEnum` or `enum.IntEnum` for enumerated types, not plain strings.
# - Use `|` operator for union types in Python 3.10+.
# - Use `match`/`case` for multi-branch conditional logic where appropriate.

# =============================================================================
# 2. ARCHITECTURE PRESERVATION RULES
# =============================================================================
# - NEVER redesign the existing RBAC system. Roles are: super_admin, admin, staff,
#   doctor, patient. Capability-based auth coexists with role-based auth.
# - NEVER remove tenant isolation. Every query must filter by tenant_id unless
#   explicitly cross-tenant (super_admin integrity scan).
# - NEVER rewrite the workspace system (backend/frontend/src/workspace/).
#   Workspace registry, resolver, route isolation, and layouts are off-limits
#   for redesign.
# - NEVER rewrite appointment invariants (appointment_invariants.py,
#   appointment_invariant_enforcement.py). These are hardened production code.
# - NEVER replace the service-layer pattern (router -> service -> crud -> ORM).
# - NEVER bypass idempotency for CREATE operations (appointments, doctors, tenants,
#   appointment completion).
# - NEVER change the global-patient architecture: patient.tenant_id is ALWAYS NULL.
#   Tenant context is derived from appointments, NOT from patient.tenant_id.
# - NEVER use role-name checks for doctor actions. Use capability-based auth via
#   get_current_doctor() + Doctor record verification.
# - NEVER trust frontend tenant IDs, role names, or JWT claims alone. Resource
#   ownership + invariants are authoritative.
# - NEVER create a separate Visit table. Appointment is the encounter anchor.
# - NEVER write to patient.tenant_id. The field exists for legacy compatibility
#   but remains permanently NULL.

# =============================================================================
# 3. BACKEND SAFETY RULES
# =============================================================================
# - All mutation endpoints must go through service layer (router -> service -> crud).
# - All service-layer mutations that touch appointments must call
#   AppointmentInvariantGuard.finalize(db, appointment_id) or
#   revalidate_appointment_invariants() before returning.
# - All CREATE operations should support Idempotency-Key header.
# - All queries must be tenant-scoped unless explicitly cross-tenant.
# - Use get_current_tenant_id() dependency for tenant resolution.
# - Use align_operation_tenant_with_resource() for mutation tenant enforcement.
# - Use assert_authorized() from security_audit for cross-tenant access validation.
# - Never use current_user.role == "doctor" for authorization. Use
#   doctor_service.get_current_doctor(db, current_user) instead.
# - Prefer explicit CRUD functions over inline queries in service layer.
# - Use ServiceError / NotFoundError / ForbiddenError / ConflictError from
#   app.services.exceptions for all error responses.
# - Use log_structured_audit_event() for critical operations.
# - Use as_db_uuid() from app.utils.db_uuids for UUID conversion in raw SQL.
# - Use non_nil_tenant_id() from app.core.tenancy to sanitize tenant UUIDs.
# - Use ensure_default_tenant_exists() at startup, never in request handlers.
# - Prefer Session.begin() context manager for transactional boundaries.

# =============================================================================
# 4. FRONTEND SAFETY RULES
# =============================================================================
# - NEVER rewrite the workspace system (registry.tsx, resolver.ts, route-isolation.tsx,
#   layouts/*, WorkspaceSwitcher.tsx).
# - NEVER bypass route isolation (route-isolation.tsx enforces workspace scoping).
# - Use the container/presentational pattern: pages fetch data, components render UI.
# - Use custom hooks for data fetching and state logic (hooks/ directory).
# - Use handler pattern for API calls (handlers/ directory).
# - Use services/ for API client functions (axios-based).
# - Use types/index.ts for shared TypeScript interfaces.
# - Use validation/schemas.ts for Zod validation schemas.
# - Use @/ path alias for imports (configured in tsconfig.json).
# - Use shadcn/ui components from components/ui/ (dialog, switch, checkbox, etc.).
# - Use lucide-react for icons.
# - Use react-hot-toast for toast notifications.
# - Use react-router-dom v7 for routing.
# - Use framer-motion for animations (components in animations/).
# - Use dayjs for date formatting.
# - Use class-variance-authority + tailwind-merge for component variants.
# - NEVER hardcode API URLs. Use services/api.ts base configuration.
# - NEVER store tokens in localStorage without understanding the security model.

# =============================================================================
# 5. MIGRATION / ALEMBIC SAFETY RULES
# =============================================================================
# - ALL migrations must be ADDITIVE only. Never drop columns or tables.
# - Never use batch operations that could lock production tables.
# - Always generate migrations with: alembic revision --autogenerate -m "description"
# - Always verify with: alembic upgrade head --sql (dry-run in offline mode).
# - Always check current state with: alembic current
# - Always review autogenerated migrations before applying.
# - Use `import app.models` in env.py to ensure all models are loaded.
# - Use `from app.core.database import Base` for metadata.
# - Use `from app.core.config import settings` for DATABASE_URL.
# - Prefer nullable columns for new fields (backward compatibility).
# - Use server_default for non-nullable new columns with existing data.
# - Never use PostgreSQL-only types in migrations that must be SQLite-compatible
#   for testing (unless the migration is explicitly @pytest.mark.postgres).
# - For CITEXT or other PG-only features, use raw SQL with dialect guards.
# - Always name revision files with descriptive prefixes (e.g., z1_, z2_).
# - Never delete old migration files.
# - Never squash migration history.
# - Keep idempotency tables (creation, completion) in sync with their source tables.
# - Migration filenames should follow the pattern: z{N}_{description}.py

# =============================================================================
# 6. TYPESCRIPT BUILD RULES
# =============================================================================
# - The frontend build command is: npx tsc -b (uses project references).
# - To type-check without emitting: npx tsc --noEmit
# - FIX unused import errors IMMEDIATELY after creating or editing any .ts/.tsx file.
# - Use `@/` path alias for all internal imports (e.g., `@/services/api`).
# - Use `import type` for type-only imports to avoid bundler issues.
# - Use `interface` over `type` for object shapes (consistent with codebase).
# - Use `type` for unions, intersections, and utility types.
# - Use `as const` for literal constants.
# - Use ` satisfies ` operator for type-safe expressions without widening.
# - Use `unknown` over `any` for values of uncertain type.
# - Use `z.infer<typeof schema>` for Zod-inferred types.
# - Keep barrel exports (index.ts files) in sync with module additions.
# - Run `npx tsc --noEmit` after any file creation or import change.
# - The tsconfig uses project references (tsconfig.app.json + tsconfig.node.json).
# - NEVER use `// @ts-ignore` or `// @ts-expect-error` without documented justification.

# =============================================================================
# 7. TESTING RULES
# =============================================================================
# - Default test database is SQLite in-memory (pytest.ini configures this).
# - PostgreSQL-only tests must use @pytest.mark.postgres marker.
# - Use factories.py for test data creation, not inline model instantiation.
# - Use conftest.py fixtures: db_session, client (httpx.AsyncClient).
# - Use pytest_asyncio for async test fixtures.
# - Use httpx.AsyncClient with ASGITransport for API tests.
# - Each test gets a clean database (autouse _reset_database fixture).
# - Test files go in backend/tests/ with test_ prefix.
# - Run tests with: pytest backend/tests/test_file.py -v
# - Run PostgreSQL tests with: $env:PYTEST_DATABASE_URL="postgresql://..."; pytest -m postgres
# - Use fast-check for property-based testing where appropriate.
# - Frontend E2E tests use Playwright: npx playwright test
# - Always write tests for new service-layer functions.
# - Always write tests for new API endpoints.
# - Test idempotency paths for CREATE operations.
# - Test tenant isolation (cross-tenant access should fail).
# - Test invariant enforcement (appointment-doctor mismatch should fail).

# =============================================================================
# 8. POWERSHELL / WINDOWS TERMINAL RULES
# =============================================================================
# - NEVER use bash syntax. This is a Windows 11 environment.
# - NEVER use `&&` to chain commands.
# - NEVER use `cmd /c` to invoke cmd.exe.
# - NEVER use Linux commands: grep, sed, awk, find, xargs, cut, sort, uniq, wc.
# - NEVER use `|` to pipe between commands (PowerShell pipes are acceptable for
#   simple object piping, but avoid complex pipelines).
# - NEVER use `;` to sequence commands on one line.
# - Use PowerShell-compatible commands ONLY.
# - Use Set-Location (or `cd`) to change directories.
# - Use Get-ChildItem (or `dir` / `ls`) to list files.
# - Use Get-Content (or `type` / `cat`) to read files.
# - Use Select-String for text search (NOT grep/findstr).
# - Use python, npx, npm, pip, alembic as direct commands (they are in PATH).
# - Use `$env:VAR_NAME="value"` to set environment variables.
# - Use `python -m venv .venv` to create virtual environments.
# - Use `.\.venv\Scripts\Activate.ps1` to activate virtual environments.

# --- GOOD PowerShell commands (use these) ---
# Set-Location "d:\Kaushal\Python\Python Projects\medical_webapp"
# npx tsc --noEmit
# pytest backend/tests/test_file.py -v
# alembic current
# python -m app.main
# npm run dev
# npm run build
# $env:DATABASE_URL="sqlite:///test.db"; pytest backend/tests/
# python -m pytest backend/tests/test_appointments.py -x -v
# npx playwright test
# alembic upgrade head
# alembic revision --autogenerate -m "description"
# pip install -r requirements.txt
# npm install

# --- BAD commands (NEVER generate these) ---
# cmd /c "cd backend && alembic upgrade head"
# npm run build && npx tsc
# grep -r "pattern" backend/
# sed -i 's/old/new/g' file.py
# awk '{print $1}' data.txt
# cat file.txt | grep pattern | sort | uniq
# cd backend && python -m app.main
# find . -name "*.py" | xargs grep "pattern"
# 2>&1 | findstr "error"
# pip install -r requirements.txt && alembic upgrade head
# npm test 2>&1 | tee output.log

# =============================================================================
# 9. ANTI-FREEZE TERMINAL EXECUTION RULES
# =============================================================================
# - NEVER chain commands with `&&`, `|`, `;`, or `||`.
# - NEVER use streaming filters that hold the terminal open (e.g., `tail -f`,
#   `--watch`, `--follow`).
# - NEVER use `|` to pipe output into filters in a way that blocks.
# - NEVER run long-running processes in a way that prevents subsequent commands.
# - Each command must be executed ONE AT A TIME.
# - Wait for command completion before issuing the next command.
# - Use `--no-pager` flags where available to prevent interactive pagers.
# - Use `-y` or `--yes` flags for package managers to prevent prompts.
# - For dev servers, use the VS Code terminal's built-in run-in-background
#   rather than backgrounding with `&` or `Start-Process`.
# - Prefer commands that exit cleanly (build, test, lint) over daemon processes.
# - If a command produces long output, redirect to a file rather than piping
#   through a pager: npx tsc --noEmit > tsc_output.txt 2>&1

# =============================================================================
# 10. OUTPUT FORMATTING RULES
# =============================================================================
# - Present changes as structured diffs (SEARCH/REPLACE blocks).
# - Show before/after context for every edit.
# - Use clear section headers when presenting multi-file changes.
# - Report progress checkpoints during long tasks.
# - Summarize what was done and what remains at each checkpoint.
# - Use task_progress parameter to track checklist completion.
# - When reporting errors, include the full error message and context.
# - When suggesting fixes, explain the root cause, not just the symptom.

# =============================================================================
# 11. FILE EDITING RULES
# =============================================================================
# - Prefer replace_in_file over write_to_file for surgical edits.
# - Use write_to_file only for new files or complete rewrites (rare).
# - After creating a new file, verify imports are correct.
# - After editing a file, check for unused imports.
# - After editing a TypeScript file, run npx tsc --noEmit to verify.
# - After editing a Python file, run pytest on related tests.
# - Never leave placeholder code, TODO comments, or commented-out code
#   unless explicitly marked with a tracked TODO.
# - Never create "stub" implementations that would compile but fail at runtime.
# - Never create fake/mock implementations that skip real logic.
# - Always verify that new files are registered in barrel exports (index.ts / __init__.py).

# =============================================================================
# 12. FORBIDDEN OPERATIONS
# =============================================================================
# - NEVER generate AI diagnosis or triage systems. This is a hospital management
#   system, not a clinical decision support system.
# - NEVER expose SOAP notes, clinical notes, or internal doctor-facing data
#   to patient-facing endpoints.
# - NEVER create duplicate/shadow healthcare tables (e.g., a second patients
#   table, a second appointments table).
# - NEVER redesign the existing architecture without explicit instruction.
# - NEVER rewrite existing RBAC or tenant isolation.
# - NEVER create dangerous migrations (destructive, non-additive).
# - NEVER generate fake code completion or placeholder APIs unless explicitly
#   marked with a tracked TODO.
# - NEVER make silent schema assumptions (always verify model fields exist).
# - NEVER create hidden migrations (always version-controlled, always reviewed).
# - NEVER use `# type: ignore` or `@ts-ignore` without documented justification.
# - NEVER commit .env files, secrets, or credentials.
# - NEVER use `print()` for production logging.
# - NEVER use `input()` in production code.
# - NEVER use `eval()` or `exec()`.
# - NEVER use `pickle` for untrusted data.

# =============================================================================
# 13. INCREMENTAL IMPLEMENTATION STRATEGY
# =============================================================================
# - Break every task into small, verifiable steps.
# - Each step must produce a working state (no half-implemented features).
# - After each step, validate: does the app still start? Do tests pass?
# - Use stop-and-validate checkpoints:
#   1. Plan the change (what files, what pattern)
#   2. Implement the change
#   3. Verify with type-checker / linter / tests
#   4. Commit or checkpoint
# - If a step would take more than 15 minutes of coding, break it further.
# - Never implement multiple independent features in a single step.
# - When fixing bugs, first write a failing test, then fix, then verify.
# - When adding features, start with the data layer (model/schema), then
#   service layer, then API, then frontend.

# =============================================================================
# 14. LONG TASK EXECUTION STRATEGY
# =============================================================================
# - For tasks estimated >30 minutes, create a phase plan first.
# - Each phase must have a clear entry/exit criteria.
# - Between phases, validate: tests pass, build succeeds, no regressions.
# - Each phase must have a rollback strategy (git revert or migration downgrade).
# - Document progress in task_progress checklist.
# - If a phase reveals unexpected complexity, stop and reassess before proceeding.
# - Never skip validation gates to "save time" — this always costs more time.
# - Long-running migrations must be tested against a copy of production data first.

# =============================================================================
# 15. REACT / TYPESCRIPT IMPORT HYGIENE RULES
# =============================================================================
# - After creating ANY new .ts/.tsx file, verify all imports resolve correctly.
# - After editing ANY .ts/.tsx file, check for unused imports and remove them.
# - Run `npx tsc --noEmit` after any import change.
# - Use barrel exports (index.ts) for directory-level exports.
# - When adding a file to a directory with an index.ts, update the index.ts.
# - Use `import type` for type-only imports to avoid runtime bundler issues.
# - Use `@/` path alias, never relative paths that traverse many levels.
# - Never import from a file's internal path if a barrel export exists.
# - Keep services/index.ts in sync with new service files.
# - Keep types/index.ts in sync with new type definitions.
# - Keep validation/index.ts in sync with new validation schemas.
# - Keep workspace/layouts/index.ts in sync with new workspace layouts.
# - Keep animations/index.ts in sync with new animation components.
# - Keep constants/index.ts in sync with new constant files.
# - Keep hooks/index.ts in sync with new hooks.
# - Keep handlers/index.ts in sync with new handlers.
# - Keep utils/index.ts in sync with new utility files.

# =============================================================================
# 16. SQLALCHEMY / POSTGRESQL COMPATIBILITY RULES
# =============================================================================
# - Prefer portable SQLAlchemy types (String, Integer, Boolean, DateTime, Text,
#   Float, Enum, UUID) over PostgreSQL-only types (ARRAY, JSONB, HSTORE, CITEXT,
#   INTERVAL, TSVECTOR) unless explicitly required.
# - When using PostgreSQL-only types, ensure the feature is gated behind
#   @pytest.mark.postgres for tests.
# - Use `Mapped[]` annotation style for column definitions (SQLAlchemy 2.0).
# - Use `mapped_column()` over deprecated `Column()`.
# - Use `relationship()` with `lazy="selectin"` or `lazy="joined"` explicitly.
# - Use `back_populates=` over `backref=` for bidirectional relationships.
# - Use `UUID` type from SQLAlchemy for primary/foreign keys.
# - Use `sa_enum` for enum types (not plain strings).
# - Use `server_default=text("now()")` for created_at timestamps.
# - Use `onupdate=func.now()` for updated_at timestamps.
# - Use `index=True` for frequently queried foreign keys.
# - Use `unique=True` with care (consider composite unique constraints).
# - Use `CompositeIndex` or `__table_args__` for multi-column indexes.
# - Verify SQLite compatibility: SQLite does not support:
#   - ARRAY, JSONB (use JSON string or separate table)
#   - CITEXT (use String + unique constraint)
#   - ENUM with custom values (use String + check constraint)
#   - DISTINCT ON (use subquery or different approach)
#   - ALTER COLUMN (use add column + drop old approach)
#   - DROP COLUMN (not supported; use recreate table approach)
#   - Schemas other than main/temp
#   - Multiple foreign key cascade paths
# - For test compatibility, prefer `text()` with dialect-specific branches
#   rather than assuming PostgreSQL features are available.

# =============================================================================
# 17. MEDICAL COMPLIANCE AND PRIVACY BOUNDARIES
# =============================================================================
# - NEVER expose SOAP notes, clinical notes, diagnosis, or treatment_summary
#   to patient-facing endpoints. These are doctor/internal only.
# - NEVER generate AI diagnosis, triage, or clinical decision support systems.
# - NEVER create endpoints that allow patients to view other patients' data.
# - NEVER expose internal audit logs to non-admin users.
# - NEVER expose idempotency keys or internal identifiers to patients.
# - Patient-accessible data is limited to: appointments (own), billing (own),
#   medication schedules (own), communication preferences (own).
# - Doctor-accessible data includes: assigned patients, own appointments,
#   clinical notes (read/write for own patients).
# - Admin-accessible data includes: tenant-wide aggregates, doctor management,
#   billing overview, integrity scans.
# - Super admin-accessible data includes: cross-tenant integrity scans,
#   tenant management, system-wide audit.
# - Always use patient_has_active_appointment_in_tenant() to verify patient
#   access within a tenant context.
# - Always use assert_authorized() for cross-tenant access validation.
# - Always log security-relevant events with log_structured_audit_event().

# =============================================================================
# 18. WORKSPACE / RBAC PRESERVATION RULES
# =============================================================================
# - NEVER rewrite workspace/registry.tsx. This is the authoritative workspace
#   registration point.
# - NEVER rewrite workspace/resolver.ts. Workspace resolution logic is hardened.
# - NEVER rewrite workspace/route-isolation.tsx. Route isolation enforces
#   workspace scoping and must not be bypassed.
# - NEVER rewrite workspace/layouts/*. These are workspace-specific layouts
#   that encapsulate navigation and structure.
# - NEVER rewrite workspace/WorkspaceSwitcher.tsx. Workspace switching logic
#   is production-tested.
# - NEVER rewrite workspace/contextual-redirects.ts. Redirect logic is
#   carefully designed for each workspace.
# - NEVER add new workspaces without registering in registry.tsx and creating
#   a layout in workspace/layouts/.
# - NEVER bypass route isolation for navigation. Always use workspace-aware
#   routing.
# - NEVER hardcode workspace IDs or role names in frontend navigation.
# - Use workspace/registry.tsx to look up workspace configurations.
# - Use workspace/resolver.ts to resolve workspace from route/context.
# - Use workspace/route-isolation.tsx to guard routes by workspace.
# - The existing workspaces are: FrontDesk, Operations, Procurement, Finance,
#   Doctor, Patient. Do not rename or restructure them.

# =============================================================================
# 19. PERFORMANCE AND DX RULES
# =============================================================================
# - Prefer surgical fixes over large refactors. Change only what is needed.
# - Use lazy imports for heavy modules (e.g., reportlab, matplotlib).
# - Use selectinload for to-many relationships to avoid N+1 queries.
# - Use joinedload for to-one relationships where the related row is always needed.
# - Use contains_eager when the relationship is already joined in the query.
# - Use limit/offset for list endpoints (pagination).
# - Use indexing for frequently filtered columns.
# - Use connection pooling (pool_pre_ping=True, pool_size, max_overflow).
# - Use caching for expensive read operations (integrity scan cache, slot cache).
# - Use Redis (Upstash REST) for distributed caching where configured.
# - Avoid loading entire tables into memory.
# - Use select [columns] instead of select [entire model] when only specific
#   columns are needed.
# - Use `__slots__` for Python data classes with many instances.
# - Use `functools.lru_cache` for pure function memoization.
# - Use `asyncio` for I/O-bound operations in FastAPI endpoints.
# - For frontend, use React.memo sparingly and only with measured benefit.
# - Use useMemo and useCallback for expensive computations, not for trivial ones.
# - Use lazy loading for route components (React.lazy + Suspense).
# - Use vite's built-in code splitting (dynamic import()).

# =============================================================================
# 20. GIT SAFETY RULES
# =============================================================================
# - NEVER force-push to main or master branches.
# - NEVER commit directly to main. Use feature branches.
# - ALWAYS review the diff before committing.
# - Use meaningful commit messages: "type(scope): description"
#   Examples: feat(appointments): add clinical notes fields
#             fix(billing): correct tax calculation for refunds
#             test(encounter): add idempotency test for completion
#             refactor(service): extract invariant validation
# - Keep commits small and focused on a single concern.
# - NEVER commit with --no-verify (bypassing hooks).
# - NEVER commit generated files (dist/, .pyc, __pycache__, node_modules/).
# - NEVER commit .env files or secrets.
# - Use .gitignore to exclude build artifacts.
# - Before committing, ensure: tests pass, type-check passes, lint passes.
# - Use `git status` to verify what will be committed.
# - Use `git diff --cached` to review staged changes.
# - Use `git add -p` for interactive staging of specific hunks.

# =============================================================================
# 21. API CONTRACT PRESERVATION RULES
# =============================================================================
# - NEVER silently change response shapes. Every API response change must be
#   coordinated with frontend consumers.
# - NEVER rename response keys without updating all consumers (frontend services,
#   types, tests, E2E tests).
# - Prefer additive response fields (add new keys, don't remove or rename old ones).
# - When adding fields to responses, ensure they are optional (nullable) for
#   backward compatibility.
# - Validate frontend/backend contract alignment: if a Pydantic schema field
#   changes, the corresponding TypeScript interface must be updated.
# - Use Pydantic's `model_dump()` with `by_alias=True` for consistent serialization.
# - Use `response_model` in FastAPI route decorators for explicit response schemas.
# - Use `status_code` in route decorators for explicit HTTP status codes.
# - Never return raw ORM models from API endpoints. Always use Pydantic schemas.
# - Never change endpoint paths without adding a redirect or alias.
# - Never change HTTP methods for existing endpoints.
# - When deprecating fields, use Pydantic's `@field_validator` with deprecation
#   warnings before removal.

# =============================================================================
# 22. RENDER / VERCEL DEPLOYMENT RULES
# =============================================================================
# - ALWAYS verify the build locally before assuming deployment will succeed.
#   Run: npm run build (frontend) and verify no TypeScript errors.
# - NEVER assume Render uses the latest artifact until confirmed. Render builds
#   from the git branch, not local files.
# - Keep migrations idempotent: `ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING` / `IF NOT EXISTS`
#   patterns so re-running migrations is safe.
# - Avoid environment-specific assumptions in code. Use settings from
#   app.core.config.Settings (loaded from environment variables).
# - Preserve cold-start safety: ensure_default_tenant_exists() is idempotent,
#   database connection validation happens in lifespan, not in request handlers.
# - Production settings enforce:
#   - REQUIRE_APPOINTMENT_COMPLETION_IDEMPOTENCY_KEY must be true
#   - SECRET_KEY must not be the dev fallback
#   - DATABASE_URL must not use SQLite
# - CORS must explicitly list allowed origins. Wildcard is not allowed for
#   credentialed requests.
# - The production frontend origin is:
#   https://hospital-management-system-nine-topaz.vercel.app
# - The production API is served by Render (or configured deployment platform).
# - Frontend build output goes to backend/frontend/dist/.
# - In production, FastAPI serves the built frontend from dist/.

# =============================================================================
# 23. ERROR HANDLING RULES
# =============================================================================
# - NEVER suppress exceptions silently. Every except block must log or explain.
# - NEVER use bare `except:` without specifying exception type(s).
# - NEVER use blanket `try/except Exception` without logging the error.
# - Prefer explicit validation errors using ValidationError from
#   app.services.exceptions.
# - Preserve HTTP status semantics:
#   - 200 OK for successful GET/PUT/PATCH
#   - 201 Created for successful POST
#   - 204 No Content for successful DELETE
#   - 400 Bad Request for validation errors
#   - 401 Unauthorized for missing/invalid authentication
#   - 403 Forbidden for insufficient permissions
#   - 404 Not Found for missing resources
#   - 409 Conflict for idempotency key conflicts / duplicate operations
#   - 422 Unprocessable Entity for Pydantic validation errors
#   - 429 Too Many Requests for rate limiting
#   - 500 Internal Server Error for unexpected errors
# - Avoid raw crashes from UUID coercion failures. Use try/except around
#   UUID() construction with meaningful error messages.
# - Avoid raw crashes from missing attributes. Use hasattr() or try/except
#   AttributeError with context.
# - Use ServiceError as the base for all service-layer exceptions.
# - Use FastAPI exception handlers for consistent error response formatting.
# - Log errors with logger.exception() for full traceback context.

# =============================================================================
# 24. SQLALCHEMY QUERY SAFETY RULES
# =============================================================================
# - NEVER reference model fields that do not exist in the database schema.
#   Always verify field names against the actual model definition.
# - Validate DISTINCT ON ordering for PostgreSQL: DISTINCT ON requires ORDER BY
#   to start with the same columns. SQLite does not support DISTINCT ON at all.
# - Avoid lazy assumptions about relationships. Always verify that a
#   relationship() exists before using it in a query.
# - Prefer explicit joins (join(), outerjoin()) over implicit relationship loading
#   for complex queries.
# - Prefer select() with specific columns over select() of entire models when
#   only a subset of columns is needed.
# - Verify SQLite compatibility when using dialect-specific features:
#   - DISTINCT ON → not supported in SQLite
#   - JSON/JSONB functions → not supported in SQLite
#   - ARRAY → not supported in SQLite
#   - Full-text search → different syntax in SQLite
#   - Window functions → supported in SQLite 3.25+ (verify version)
# - Use `with_for_update()` for pessimistic locking in PostgreSQL (skip in SQLite).
# - Use `execution_options(schema_translate_map={...})` for multi-schema queries.
# - Use `text()` with bound parameters for raw SQL, never f-strings.
# - Use `aliased()` for self-referential joins.

# =============================================================================
# 25. FRONTEND ROUTING SAFETY RULES
# =============================================================================
# - NEVER hardcode literal route params like `:id` in navigation code.
#   Use template strings or route builder functions.
# - Use `useParams()` to extract route parameters, never parse from window.location.
# - Validate navigation paths after route refactors. Run the app and click through
#   affected routes.
# - Preserve backward-compatible redirects when renaming routes.
# - Use `useNavigate()` for programmatic navigation, never window.location.href.
# - Use `<Link>` for declarative navigation, never `<a>` tags for internal routes.
# - Use workspace-aware routing: routes are scoped by workspace in route-isolation.tsx.
# - Route patterns:
#   - / → workspace resolver
#   - /login, /signup, /reset-password → auth routes (no workspace)
#   - /admin/* → admin workspace
#   - /doctor/* → doctor workspace
#   - /patient/* → patient workspace
#   - /front-desk/* → front desk workspace
#   - /operations/* → operations workspace
#   - /procurement/* → procurement workspace
#   - /finance/* → finance workspace
# - Use workspace/contextual-redirects.ts for post-login redirect resolution.
# - Use workspace/resolver.ts to determine which workspace a user should see.

# =============================================================================
# 26. OPERATIONAL WORKFLOW INVARIANTS
# =============================================================================
# - Appointment remains the encounter anchor. Never create a separate Visit
#   or Encounter table that duplicates appointment semantics.
# - Billing invariants cannot be bypassed:
#   - Bill.tenant_id must match Appointment.tenant_id
#   - Bill.appointment_id must reference a valid appointment
#   - Bill status transitions: pending → paid (no reverse)
#   - Idempotency for bill creation where applicable
# - Medication schedules are derived layers only:
#   - PatientMedicationSchedule is a patient-level entity, not a visit entity
#   - Medication adherence logs are audit records, not clinical orders
#   - Medication schedules do not affect billing or inventory directly
# - Procurement/inventory mutations must remain auditable:
#   - All inventory movements must have a reference type and ID
#   - Purchase orders track status transitions (draft → ordered → received → cancelled)
#   - Inventory consumption is linked to appointments via AppointmentInventoryUsage
# - Queue transitions must preserve operational state flow:
#   - ClinicQueueEntry status: waiting → in_consultation → completed / cancelled
#   - Queue status transitions are one-directional (no going back)
#   - Queue entries are tenant-scoped and appointment-linked
# - Operational alerts are informational, not transactional:
#   - Alerts do not block operations
#   - Alert severity levels: critical, warning, info
#   - Alerts are tenant-scoped
# - Staff tasks are assignment records:
#   - Tasks are assigned to users within a tenant
#   - Task status: pending → in_progress → completed
#   - Tasks are not workflow blockers

# =============================================================================
# ANTI-HALLUCINATION RULES
# =============================================================================
# - NEVER generate code that references files, functions, or classes that do not
#   exist in this repository. Verify existence before referencing.
# - NEVER assume the existence of database columns, indexes, or constraints
#   without checking the model definition or migration history.
# - NEVER assume the existence of API endpoints, query parameters, or response
#   fields without checking the router/schema definitions.
# - NEVER generate fake code completion. If you are unsure about an implementation
#   detail, ask or use a TODO marker.
# - NEVER create placeholder APIs that return hardcoded data unless explicitly
#   marked with a tracked TODO and wrapped in a feature flag.
# - NEVER make silent schema assumptions. Always read the model file to verify
#   field names, types, and relationships.
# - NEVER create hidden migrations. Every migration must be a version-controlled
#   file in backend/alembic/versions/.
# - NEVER assume a package, library, or tool is installed without checking
#   requirements.txt, package.json, or node_modules before use.
